Here's the typical registration pattern:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient + data service — one instance for the whole app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — new instance each time they're requested
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — new instance each navigation
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`; shared state (caches, auth tokens) should live once. |
| `MainViewModel` | **Transient** | Each page navigation gets fresh state — no stale data leaking between visits. |
| `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Same reason; the detail item changes per navigation. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the transient ViewModels; avoids binding to a stale VM after re-navigation. |

**Key rules of thumb:**
- **Singleton** → stateless or intentionally shared (HTTP clients, caches, config).
- **Transient** → anything tied to a user interaction or navigation (ViewModels, pages).
- **Scoped** → rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET); avoid unless you define custom scopes.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **transient** dependency into a **singleton** — it effectively becomes a singleton too and won't refresh. The DI container will not warn you.
